to make any statement about
they're underpaid or overpaid,

00:09:49.247 --> 00:09:51.580
especially relative to some
people I knew in the finance

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:53.360
world, I would say that
they're definitely underpaid.

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:54.200
LAURENCE BAKER: Possibly, yes.

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:54.908
SALMAN KHAN: Yes.

00:09:54.908 --> 00:09:58.150
They're above Mercedes
in that world.

00:09:58.150 --> 00:10:00.800
And so are we getting
anything in exchange for this?

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:03.117
Are we getting less wait times?

00:10:03.117 --> 00:10:04.950
Are we getting better
access to our doctors?

00:10:04.950 --> 00:10:07.030
What are we getting or
what do we know about that?

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:08.863
LAURENCE BAKER: Well,
so this is the debate.

00:10:08.863 --> 00:10:11.260
This is in, maybe, a microcosm
one of the big debates

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:12.640
we're having in
the US right now.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:13.830
We're spending more every year.

00:10:13.830 --> 00:10:15.538
We're spending more
than other countries.

00:10:15.538 --> 00:10:18.197
If it was clear we were twice
as well off, twice as happy--

00:10:18.197 --> 00:10:19.780
SALMAN KHAN: And
we're growing faster.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:20.920
LAURENCE BAKER: And
we're growing-- yes, it

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:22.503
depends on how you
look at the timing,

00:10:22.503 --> 00:10:24.870
but we're growing a little
faster in some years.

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:26.340
Our health care costs go up 10%.

00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:28.580
If we knew we were 10% happier
this year with our health care

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:29.730
system, we would be happy.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:31.950
And that's the big debate.

00:10:31.950 --> 00:10:34.614
There are some cases
where the US-- there

00:10:34.614 --> 00:10:35.780
are things you can point to.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:38.790
We have fewer waiting
lines for some services,

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:40.260
and some of the
countries that keep

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.769
the costs down have more lines.

00:10:42.769 --> 00:10:44.310
It's also not the
case that they have

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:46.430
waiting lines for everything
and the really serious stuff

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:48.230
doesn't tend to have
long waiting lines.

00:10:48.230 --> 00:10:52.390
We get easier access to some
of the high tech stuff, which

00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:54.390
we like it, and so that
drives up our spending

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:56.159
but maybe makes us happy.

00:10:56.159 --> 00:10:58.450
SALMAN KHAN: It may or may
not lead to better outcomes.

00:10:58.450 --> 00:10:59.825
So it makes us
happy that we feel

00:10:59.825 --> 00:11:02.300
like we're getting
better customer service.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:03.505
Instead of waiting three
months for a procedure,

00:11:03.505 --> 00:11:06.046
we're getting it in three weeks,
which would make me happier.

00:11:06.046 --> 00:11:08.560
I mean, objectively, I would
be much happier about that.

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:12.140
But what happens when we
look at the overall outcomes?

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:15.700
Life expectancy, and people
dying from heart disease,

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:17.267
or whatever?

00:11:17.267 --> 00:11:19.100
LAURENCE BAKER: This
is kind of a mixed bag.

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:21.370
Some of the most
commonly cited figures

00:11:21.370 --> 00:11:23.200
are cases where
the US doesn't do

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:25.727
as well as some
European countries.

00:11:25.727 --> 00:11:28.310
We spend a lot more and we don't
do better on life expectancy.

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.260
We don't do better
an infant mortality.

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:32.720
There are some cases where
the US does really well,

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:36.174
especially things where
access to the high end stuff

00:11:36.174 --> 00:11:37.090
can make a difference.

00:11:37.090 --> 00:11:38.673
And so there are
some situations where

00:11:38.673 --> 00:11:41.545
it looks like we buy the kinds
of things that are really

00:11:41.545 --> 00:11:42.670
going to make us healthier.

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:44.670
But it's not across the board.

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:46.310
And some of the really
interesting ones

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:48.500
are cases where there's
fairly inexpensive stuff

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:51.300
that looks like it would work
well and improve outcomes,

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:53.959
and sometimes we're not
doing the inexpensive stuff

00:11:53.959 --> 00:11:55.250
that other countries are doing.

00:11:55.250 --> 00:11:59.290
And it's coming out
to maybe hurt us.

00:11:59.290 --> 00:12:02.180
We wouldn't be having the debate
if we were clearly better off,

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:04.680
but it's really the case that,
in only some of the measures,

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:05.670
do we end up better off.

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:07.336
We don't always
vaccinate our kids more.

00:12:07.336 --> 00:12:09.040
We don't always get
people screened more

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.680
for cancers and
things like that.

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:12.200
But sometimes we do.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.170
So there are success
stories here.

00:12:14.170 --> 00:12:15.830
SALMAN KHAN: Now,
one thing that's

00:12:15.830 --> 00:12:17.470
interesting about looking
at this chart a little bit

00:12:17.470 --> 00:12:19.720
deeper is that it doesn't
look like this is something

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:21.594
that, you know, since
the American Revolution

00:12:21.594 --> 00:12:24.117
that we've been spending
double as a percentage of GDP

00:12:24.117 --> 00:12:25.200
relative to everyone else.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.210
I mean if I just look at
this chart right here,

00:12:27.210 --> 00:12:30.110
it seems like us and
Canada, we were right along

00:12:30.110 --> 00:12:33.180
very similar to each other
to about the early '70s.

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:35.405
And then we're still
in kind of that pack

00:12:35.405 --> 00:12:37.210
with Germany and France.

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:39.680
I guess, relative to the
UK, we actually always

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:40.570
have been higher.

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:43.010
But then right around
this time period,

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:45.190
the late '70s,
early '80s-- that's

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:47.290
where we really
started to break off.

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:49.240
Was there some
policy shift there?

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:51.730
LAURENCE BAKER: So there's not
a tangible, specific policy

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:52.230
shift.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:55.080
What starts happening in the
US there is we start adopting

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.442
and we start shifting toward
the higher-end stuff more.

00:12:57.442 --> 00:12:58.650
And some of that's the part--

00:12:58.650 --> 00:13:00.649
SALMAN KHAN: That's where
the technology started

00:13:00.649 --> 00:13:01.390
to really get--

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:03.390
LAURENCE BAKER: I think
that's mainly the story.

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:06.450
We started to
really-- the research

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:09.040
in things, the development that
went on in the world, really

00:13:09.040 --> 00:13:12.500
from 1940, '50, '60, started
to produce the capacity

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:14.430
to do new and expensive things.

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:17.060
And the US grabbed those and
other countries in the world

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:19.325
were less quick to
grab them, maybe,

00:13:19.325 --> 00:13:20.450
you would say more careful.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:22.560
Maybe you would say
too careful, too slow.

00:13:22.560 --> 00:13:26.450
But the US, as you see
there, really quickly started

00:13:26.450 --> 00:13:28.550
to put up specialized
hospitals, started

00:13:28.550 --> 00:13:30.930
to buy the fancy
equipment, and you

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:32.960
can see what kind
of came out of it.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.070
SALMAN KHAN: And to some degree,
probably, the whole world

00:13:34.070 --> 00:13:36.490
benefited from that because
you're going back to the drug

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:40.210
pricing or the MRI manufacturers
were able to get those returns

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:42.710
and, hopefully,
much of that they're

00:13:42.710 --> 00:13:45.370
able to reinvest and not spend
too much on other things.

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:47.850
But it is fueling--

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:49.909
LAURENCE BAKER: Yeah,
the innovation-- there's

00:13:49.909 --> 00:13:52.200
always these kinds of questions
that swirl around here.

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:53.480
If the US pays a lot
of money and that

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:55.813
comes back into innovation
then everybody benefits from,

00:13:55.813 --> 00:13:57.854
including us, maybe it's OK.

00:13:57.854 --> 00:13:59.770
I think there are people
who debate whether we

00:13:59.770 --> 00:14:01.970
got enough innovation,
enough benefits that's

00:14:01.970 --> 00:14:05.960
tangibly related to our spending
to make our spending worth it,

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:08.230
but there are some cases
where that probably happened.

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:11.490
And so there's some
subtlety to the question.

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:13.030
I always say, if
you're the Yankees

00:14:13.030 --> 00:14:16.460
and you're going to pay the
huge amount for the big payroll

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:19.570
and the big stars, people
expect you to win every time.

00:14:19.570 --> 00:14:20.890
And that's the US's challenge.

00:14:20.890 --> 00:14:21.930
If we're going to
pay the big bucks--

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:22.820
SALMAN KHAN: We
should show results.

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:23.420
LAURENCE BAKER:
--we really like we

00:14:23.420 --> 00:14:25.080
want to show results every time.

00:14:25.080 --> 00:14:26.790
And sometimes we
do get the results,

00:14:26.790 --> 00:14:27.997
but it's not often enough.

00:14:27.997 --> 00:14:29.330
SALMAN KHAN: It's not ambiguous.

00:14:29.330 --> 00:14:32.020
We're not winning the
championship every year.

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:33.830
Very interesting.

